card.desc:
#### Overview

The “acronyms & terminology” exercise is an excellent place to start as it requires no pre-requisite knowledge and each card in the list can be completed in as little as two minutes.

It’s a great way to slowly “get the ball rolling”, which is the hardest part for most people.

Additionally, this exercise will dramatically increase conversational confidence when speaking with other business professionals in the broader IT eco-system and will most certainly surface new learning paths to explore.

---

**How To Complete This Exercise:**

Whenever you have a few minutes to spare, simply click into a card and open a new tab in your browser.

From there, just do a simple google search for the acronym, technology, term within that card and read a bit about this topic (spend no more than a few minutes on each topic).

- For example: “What is Javascript?”

Once you’re done, simply copy/paste any relevant information that you found as a comment into the card. Google will oftentimes create a summary of the search term on the right hand side of the page from Wikipedia.

- For example: JavaScript, often abbreviated as JS, is a programming language that is one of the core technologies of the World Wide Web, alongside HTML and CSS. As of 2022, 98% of websites use JavaScript on the client side for web page behavior, often incorporating third-party libraries.

Also feel free to add any thoughts or questions you might have so that we can address them later.

That’s it! We’re essentially building our own dictionary of terms that we can use throughout the learning process.

Feel free to add new cards for yourself as well.

Remember, the goal of this exercise is NOT to become an expert on anything. We’re simply trying to understand some of the terminology that might arise on your journey and become more conversational.

---

**Sample Conversation:**

**Interviewer**: _Do you have any experience working with ERP systems?_

**You:** _Although I don’t have any working experience with Enterprise Resource + Planning systems, I understand that it’s a crucial component for most businesses and I’m currently learning more about the SAP ERP Solution. From what I’ve read, this is a very popular ERP solution, correct?_

#### Career Mentorship Program Overview:

> _**How did this program start?**_
>
> Crossroads, no longer walking reaction to my traumas and fears, met myself for the first time, set out to build the exact life I want for myself, philosophy – big thing to work on, search for meaning, happiness must ensue, it cannot be pursued, biggest goal (500 people).
>
> _**Why do I do this? What’s in it for me?**_
>
> That’s simple; this gives my life meaning. As an added bonus, I’ve met some truly remarkable people and learned much from them in the process.
>
> IIt's worth noting that this "purpose" isn't fueled by some magical, altruistic light inside of me. It's more of a debt that I owe the universe for allowing me to escape from a difficult, troubled early life that I most certainly did not ask for or deserve. The price is more than fair in my book, and I have no intentions of stopping any time soon.
>
> _**What makes this program special?**_
>
> Unique career path, behind the scenes look at careers, more about becoming an extraordinary problem solver and solving nearly any problem a potential employer or customer may ask of you, learning always (oftentimes on your employers dime), focusing on the hard skills that most people avoid but make a world of difference.
>
> _**What are the steps involved with the mentorship program?**_
>
> _**How much time do I need to allot towards this?**_
>
> _**How can you guarantee employment?**_

#### First Steps:

- Trello Board Setup
- Career Path Exploration + Exercise
- Goal Setting Workshop

#### Learning Phase:

- Confirm Career Path
- Build Lesson Plan
- Weekly Check In (Road Block Resolution, Accountability)

#### Online Resume Project:

- Planning
- Building
- Launching / Testing
- LinkedIn Finalization

#### Game Time:

- Define Job Search, Application Routine
- Apply, Interview (High Touch)
- Employment

#### Yearly Check In:

- Status Report
- Pivots Required?
- New Plan (If Needed)

cards.desc:
#### Overview

The “acronyms & terminology” exercise is an excellent place to start as it requires no pre-requisite knowledge and each card in the list can be completed in as little as two minutes.

It’s a great way to slowly “get the ball rolling”, which is the hardest part for most people.

Additionally, this exercise will dramatically increase conversational confidence when speaking with other business professionals in the broader IT eco-system and will most certainly surface new learning paths to explore.

---

**How To Complete This Exercise:**

Whenever you have a few minutes to spare, simply click into a card and open a new tab in your browser.

From there, just do a simple google search for the acronym, technology, term within that card and read a bit about this topic (spend no more than a few minutes on each topic).

- For example: “What is Javascript?”

Once you’re done, simply copy/paste any relevant information that you found as a comment into the card. Google will oftentimes create a summary of the search term on the right hand side of the page from Wikipedia.

- For example: JavaScript, often abbreviated as JS, is a programming language that is one of the core technologies of the World Wide Web, alongside HTML and CSS. As of 2022, 98% of websites use JavaScript on the client side for web page behavior, often incorporating third-party libraries.

Also feel free to add any thoughts or questions you might have so that we can address them later.

That’s it! We’re essentially building our own dictionary of terms that we can use throughout the learning process.

Feel free to add new cards for yourself as well.

Remember, the goal of this exercise is NOT to become an expert on anything. We’re simply trying to understand some of the terminology that might arise on your journey and become more conversational.

---
